items.name: Панельки (Khrushchevka Diffusion)
items.description:
About

English

The model is trained on panel-constructed apartment blocks — so-called Khrushchevka buildings or more recently Panelki (Панельки). As they have been built in ambudance all over the USSR and the Eastern Block, a large amount of people living inside the post-soviet region have been raised in them and thus panelki have left a strong trace in their memories. Their grayish look and cheap, mass-produced structure made them the symbol of futurelessness, loneliness inside the crowd and depression. In recent times, the repeating pattern, decaying and crowded nature gained them the reputation of eldritch structures, for example, reflected in the fandom of Samosbor where the action happens inside the infinite Gigakhrushchevka.

Russian (Русский)

Модель обучена на панельных квартирных блоках — так называемых «хрущёвках» или, с недавних пор, «панельками». Поскольку их строили в чрезмерных количествах по всему СССР и странам Варшавского договора, значительное число людей на постсоветском пространстве провели в них своё детство, и посему панельки оставили нестираемый след в их памяти. Серый внешний вид и дешёвое строение, предназначенное для массового производства, сделало их символом безысходности, одиночества в толпе и уныния. В последнее время повторяющаяся структура, обветшалость и теснота заслужили им славу непостижимых мистических объектов, что, к примеру, отражает фандом Самосбора, где действие происходит внутри бесконечно большой Гигахрущёвки.

items.name: Hellscape - A world of demons, zombies, gore and horror - Model 2.1 Embedding by SoCalGuitarist
items.description:
This is Hellscape, a world stuck in time after the gates of hell swung wide! Hellscape has been several weeks and over 100 hours in the making, with multiple revisions to try to make it as flexible and coherent as possible, while still delivering on the demonic vision I set out to achieve.

Hellscape delivers bleak yet atmospheric vistas, deteriorating infrastructure and oh yeah, demons and zombies and all sorts of other nasty ghoulies. If you're making zombies, use expressive words like "rotting flesh rancid meat bloated corpse" to really pile on the effects (careful, it can get downright gross if you push it too far!) while demons really react well to flavor words like "terror, fear, hopelessness, blight" and other apocalyptic delights.

Hellscape was also trained on anatomically correct training images, so it's also pretty good at knowing what a human nipple looks like... For best results for females, "nude with her breasts exposed" will typically land you proper nipples, though you may still need to neg clothing and "pasties" if it's fighting you. #freethenipple

I want to give special thanks to my friend masslevel for helping me conceptualize, test, refine, and improve Hellscape over the many hours of revisions and re-dos! He also donated many of the great images used for the listing here. Check him out on twitter, he does some really amazing things in the latent space!

NOTE - Hellscape comes on pretty strong - if you're finding it looks "burnt", try running it with a lower CFG around the 4 - 5 range, and you can also try de-emphasizing Hellscape to about 75% strength, like this: (Hellscape768:0.75)

As with all of my other embeds, Hellscape has been designed to be as flexible and cohesive as possible. It responds best to short prompts, and it mixes nicely with my Cinema768 series, especially the digital and analog variants. Hellscape also responds well to my Fix yo' ugly Face Facelift embedding, however fair warning, if you want you want ugly monsters, leave Facelift on the sideline! You can find all of my other high quality embeddings on my profile page, follow me to be notified when I release new embeddings!

--------

To use this embedding in AUTOMATIC1111, copy it to your embeddings folder in your stable-diffusion-webui directory. No need to restart, just invoke the embedding from your prompt. Make sure you are using a compatible model or you will get errors!

--------

items.name: HiRyS, it's AI-RyS! (LoRA)
items.description:
WARNING: This model was briefly auto-hidden by CivitAI for preview images containing 'loli' content. There was no such thing in the removed images - the only difference between them and the images that were approved to stay up is that the removed ones had 'hololive' in the prompt. If you want to post your gens using this LORA, make sure not to use 'hololive' in the prompt, or scrub the EXIF data first!

The base Anything and NAI models aren't so great at generating images of a certain virtual YouTuber with horns, halos, and a gorgeous voice. Here's an attempt to fix that!

ALPHA VERSION: This is literally my second attempt at training a LoRA. I've gotten some good results with it but visual artifacts are common and unusual prompts may give some very low-quality outputs. I hope to upload better versions as I learn more about LoRA training.

Trained using AnythingV3 fp32 and its corresponding VAE; use those for best results. I've had some success using it with other models but results may vary.

For best results, use keywords that describe her in your prompt - e.g. long hair, multiple horns, [red|purple] hair, fangs, and perhaps her name as well. No trigger words are necessary to get a good approximation of her standard appearance, but here are some things to try:

  • white dress is likely to get her official outfit; it's a bit overtrained so try putting it in your negative prompt if you want her in something else.

  • official_outfit is, in theory, keyed to that official outfit as well, but it doesn't seem to affect output much. Again, I'm still learning; hopefully future versions will be better!

  • kimono is likely to get her alternate outfit, although this one isn't well-trained and often comes out distorted or too short.

  • double halo and star halo for better chances of getting her distinctive halos.

If artifacting is particularly bad on a prompt you're attempting, try turning the LoRA strength down and adding more keywords describing her to the prompt - I usually get best results around 0.75-0.85 strength.

(note: if Cover so much as gazes in my direction this is gone. Please do not sell images generated with this LoRA, sell or provide paid access to the LoRA itself or merges or retrains of it, or use this LoRA as part of a paid service.)

items.name: Studio Ghibli Style LoRA
items.description:
Studio Ghibli style LoRA

Making models can be expensive. Do you like what I do? Consider supporting me on Patreon 🅿️ or feel free to buy me a coffee ☕

I know there are already various Ghibli models, but with LoRA being a thing now it's time to bring this style into 2023. This is good around 1 weight for the offset version and 0.65 for the old one, on Anything v4.5 for a more authentic style, but it's also good on AbyssOrangeMix2. Triggers with ghibli style and, as you can see, it should work with any character LoRA or TI that didn't overfit on style too. Keep in mind, this is a style model not a "Ghibli characters" model, so movie characters in the examples are made using careful prompting, meaning it can reproduce similar characters, but it won't make them perfectly (unless you also use other TI/LoRA's).

4th pic by Karkaz using also his own character LoRA.

Last pic by LottaLewds.


How to use LoRA's in auto1111:

  • Update webui (use git pull like here or redownload it)

  • Copy the file to stable-diffusion-webui/models/lora

  • Select your LoRA like in this video

  • Make sure to change the weight if needed (by default it's :1)

items.name: card-style a 2.1 embedding for the modern digital fantasy style.
items.description:
card-style is the token for versions 1 and 2. The new version 3 was trained from the ground up using the same dataset and has a new token, cardstyleV3.

All of the v2 and v3 images are using the v2-1_768-nonema-pruned.ckpt checkpoint.

Trained on 140+ images (260+ for v2) from a variety of modern digital artists for card and videos games such as Gwent and Magic the Gathering. All of the artists have a similar style which has let me get something from the 2.1 checkpoint I was previously unable to achieve. I also recommend using the 2.1 trained checkpoint Ultra Cmodel. I suspect it used similar training images or it's just this modern style which everyone seems to be using. I also tested it with the PRMJ checkpoint, the final image sample was made using it.

items.name: Ranma Style LORA
items.description:
A LORA trained to imitate the style of late '80s early 90's anime specifically, the Ranma 1/2 anime. It's similar to my Ranma 1/2 checkpoint, but it's not an extraction from the .ckpt, rather I trained the LORA from scratch with a tweaked data set. IMO the the main differences between them is, that the LORA seems to do a better job with full bodies and it lacks the graininess, slight blur and the sort of analog feel the .ckpt has.

As with most other LORA you're going to have to change the strength to somewhere between .4-.7 otherwise it will probably overpower and distort your results. It was trained with Anything V3, so it should work with it's various offshoots.

My training parameters were:

  • max_resolution: 512,512,

  • learning_rate: 1e-4,

  • train_batch_size: 1,

  • epoch: 5",

  • mixed_precision: fp16,

  • save_precision: fp16

  • text_encoder_lr: 5e-5,

  • unet_lr: 1e-4,

  • clip_skip: 2,

items.name: Mirajane embedding
items.description:
This is an embedding to invoke Mirajane Strauss from Fairy Tail in your prompts.

How to use it ? Simply put the file in the 'embeddings' folder and add 'abcdef_mirajane' to your prompt tags.

It's my first embedding, and even if I like the final result with the right parameters, there is some troubles sometime; here few suggestions to avoid them :

  • Use a good mixed model to avoid blurry results (mine is OrangeCocoa 50/50 Mix from Corneo).

  • Always start with a lot of quality tags (like 'masterpiece, best quality, hyper detailed, highres, official art, 8k, (realistic:1.1)').

  • There still sometimes a crossing out on the picture, especialy on eyes; or a watermark.

If you follow these steps you should get the same quality results as mine.

Good generations !

items.name: Chrissie Mayr
items.description:
Big shoutout to @Athos252 and his original https://civitai.com/models/5303/chrissie-mayr that included the testing data!

Also shoutout to @scruffynerf for "nagging" me to try the TI :-)

And of course to @justmaier :)

And to Aitrepreneur and his great guide regarding TI:

I've used training data from @Athos252 (big thanks for it, I have no clue why other people DO NOT INCLUDE training data, after all, we are here to share the models AND the knowledge, right?

For the first positive result, I decided to not stray away from the suggested parameters from the guide, so everything was set that way.

To be honest I am quite happy with the result and I do not understand why we have on Civitai so many TIs of famous people that BARELY resemble them (yes, the similarity, for the most part, is there, but nobody will be fooled in thinking that it could be an actual photograph of such person).


I, by no means, claim that mine is that good (I still believe that perfect Dreambooth beats perfect TI, however good enough TI can beat good enough Dreambooth, so - in a sense, @scruffynerf is correct that usually, a TI is sufficient) but I think it's good enough :)

Also, shoutout to lovely Chrissie Mayr which I was a fan of before seeing her TI on Civitai. She has a great sense of humor and does not beat around the bush. Her youtube channel is worth checking out!! (https://www.youtube.com/@ChrissieMayr/videos)

I have made the following versions available:

chrissiem-600, chrissiem-1000, chrissiem-2000, chrissiem-3000

They all have their own purposes (600 is the most flexible, while the others can be used for more photorealistic versions with a degree of variety).

As a showcase of the model, I've uploaded my generations that were done purely with AUTOMATIC1111 (no photoshop or any other improvements). However, some were direct generations and some were generations with inpainting on top (easy to find out the inpaintings as I was using Huen @ 150 for them)

Big shoutout to @Athos252 and his original https://civitai.com/models/5303/chrissie-mayr

items.name: Gillian Anderson
items.description:
I'm remaking my checkpoints into TIs since I am now able to generate them, which should make certain people happy :-)

There are several versions (by epochs). The longer the training goes the more accurate the model should be but also less flexible so pick and choose according to your current needs.

You can go through the examples and in the metadata you will see which version was used (since they are not sorted and uploaded per .pt version!)

As done with my first test embedding (Chrissie Mayr) - some were done as pure outputs and some were later hit with inpainting, but there was no photoshopping involved. What you see is what you get.

Also, I do not use 'restore faces' option because it changes the face structure too much and the person becomes less recognizable. But this is something that can be fixed in post.

items.name: SamDoesArts (Sam Yang) Style LoRA
items.description:
SamDoesArts (Sam Yang) style LoRA

Making models can be expensive. Do you like what I do? Consider supporting me on Patreon 🅿️ or feel free to buy me a coffee ☕

There are already countless models for this artstyle, but I still wanted to test out how LoRA's can handle it. I also wanted to experiment with AnyPastel (or Anime Pastel Dream - Soft). This LoRA didn't come out super strong, so it has the right flexibility to get a style that's closer to Sam Yang's on AnyPastel, while still reminding of him on other models. Check the examples (mainly the model hash) to get what I mean. Triggers with sam yang and I suggest AnyPastel as base model (or, if you don't care about having a more matching artstyle, AnyLoRA or AbyssOrangeMix2). Use weight=1 for the offset version or 0.65 for the original (check "original" tab for a comparison).

The pic of Melina is also using my Melina LoRA.

Pic 3 and last 4 ones (all the realistic ones) have been made by kaynite using NED.


How to use LoRA's in auto1111:

  • Update webui (use git pull like here or redownload it)

  • Copy the file to stable-diffusion-webui/models/lora

  • Select your LoRA like in this video

  • Make sure to change the weight according to the instructions (by default it's :1)

items.name: Hatsune Miku (Magical Mirai 2015)
items.description:
This is my first LoRA I trained with Kohya scripts and Easy Training Scripts by Derrian Distro of a favorite Hatsune Miku variant of mine.

At first I trained it with Anything 4.5 model, 4 epochs and 5 repeats and results weren't bad but I thought I could've used more, so in comes Apyr (which I cannot thank enough), who used 2 epochs with 40 repeats on my dataset consisting of 36 images and it came out better than before, but he used WebUI with NAI model to train it. Still I'm quite proud of how it came out in the end.

Refeer to the trigger tags on the right in order to get Miku generated with her Magical Mirai 2015/Hand in Hand costume, it works pretty well with Anything and AOM2 when I tested it myself.

modelVersions.name: Improved
modelVersions.description:
I re-trained this LoRA using settings from a rentry called 'LAZY TRAINING GUIDE' and NAI model. I added lots of new images from dataset (this time with 2 repeats) while removing some s***** ones and edited some to remove text and other distracting elements, I also pruned clothing and body tags so that you only need to use two trigger words to generate her each time without having to describe her at all. I lastly resized it with dim at 8 using Derrian Distro's LoRA Resize script from his collection of scripts you can find on his Github.

It now generates her even better than before in greater quality, which I'm severely impressed by it a lot more than the first time I trained it.

This is a LoRA trained on classic jockstraps. Primarily, the Bike Vintage Throwback, Bike white classic 7110 vintage jockstrap. After much experimentation, this version now allows you to use different characters and body types. Trained on 512x512 images, and white, yellow, and red jockstraps.

  • Dial the weight down to 0.8 to allow the checkpoint you're using to have more of an influence on the outputs.

Making models can be expensive. Do you like what I do? Consider supporting me on Patreon 🅿️ or feel free to buy me a coffee ☕


This is one of my favorite series. I decided to do this LoRA because I noticed that there is very little western animation style in any SD model.

First 3 and last 3 example of season 1 images are characters from my D&D group. I remade all of them for season 1+2 version.


How to use LoRA's in auto1111:

  • Update webui (use git pull like here or redownload it)

  • Copy the file to stable-diffusion-webui/models/lora

  • Select your LoRA like in this video

  • Make sure to change the weight (by default it's :1 which is usually too high)

items.name: Shirtlift: a LORA for flashing tits
items.description:
SEQUEL OUT NOW: Skirtlift

I was having a hard time prompting a woman lifting her shirt, so I made this LORA. It also works for men.

Sample images made with the model Liberty.

EDIT: some people asked how I made it. Here's a rough guide:

Workflow:

1. Scour the interweb for pictures that represent the theme (women pulling their shirts up). Try to get a range of bodytypes/outfits/locations (while keeping in mind that they need to still have enough of a consistent theme for the AI pick up on what's being trained)

2. Crop and tag images. It's better to crop manually, especially with smaller datasets, but I had over 100 images so I automated it and just deleted the bad crops. (Many tools available for this. I think I used the Smart Process extension for Automatic1111).

2a. Cut the tags that represent the theme ('flashing,' 'pulling back shirt,' etc.), replace with a universal tag ('shirtlift')

2b. Fix incorrect tags

3. Run a first LORA training (I used the Kohya LoRA Fine-Tuning Notebook by Linaqruf).

4. Test it with an uncomplicated prompt and see what's not working:

4a. Is it not grasping the theme? Cut images that are too much of a variation on the theme (here it was mostly shots where the shirt was too bunched up to for the AI to 'read' it as a shirt, and shots where other things were going on with the person's hands)

4b. Is it reproducing aspects that aren't essential to the theme? Cut some of the images that over-represent those aspects in the dataset and/or describe those aspects in the caption since the AI might be assuming they're part of the universal tag. (Here it was forcing some of the same facial features or bodytypes)

4c. Is it just being wonky in some indescribable way? Change the training settings. (This is still trial and error for me but there are some guides out there)

4d. Repeat step 3 with those changes

5. Repeat step 4 using more complicated prompts to see if it can carry the theme over to different styles and situations that weren't represented in the dataset.

5a. If it's having trouble reproducing something you really want, try to find examples of that thing to add it to the dataset.

6. Repeat step 5 until satisfied.

Settings

I ended up with 104 images after a couple rounds of trimming out unhelpful ones.

The settings were mostly the defaults in Linaqruf's Kohya Lora Fine-tuner notebook, but with these changes:

Model: SD1.5

mixed_precision: FP16

Network Dim + Network_Alpha: 64

LR_Scheduler: cosine_with_restarts

Dataset_Repeats: 2

Clip_Skip: 1

I don't know how important some of them are; I'm still trial-and-erroring this thing.

For more info, this is a helpful guide I learned from.
